But we may well suppose that, guided by his prevailing tastes, he was constantly occupied at Athens with Attic literature, and especially with the immortal produc- tions of the Attio Muse. Doubtless he studied Homer again, perhaps in the identical copy he had thumbed over at school, and he now read the great poet with a sense of freedom and a lively- intelligent interest he had never felt under the rule of Orbilius; and to his more willing mind and more mature intelleot the tale of Achilles’ wrath‚⁸ and of the wanderings of Ulysses‚ now began to reveal, as they had never done before, all their wondrous significance.
